comments.text:
I own a Managed IT Service Provider. We've successfully integrated the custom AI project model on a retainer basis (customer pays us $xxxx/mo and we develop agents/apps, host them, etc.). I think it works well in this situation, as an addon to our existing service business. We have an existing base of customers who already trust us and already pay us on a monthly basis for IT. We're also already intimately familiar with their workflows (and in many cases helped create those workflows over years of them being a customer), the LOB apps they use, and so on.

But I'm also working on creating an AI SaaS company that creates productized apps/AI. I think in the long run, this is where I want to be. To be honest, service businesses are a never-ending nightmare. lol

comments.text: Sass is dying. Not saying you can still make a buck or two. What you should do is to do "one-off" projects and continue to learning from them and keep adding more value (that's the "reoccurring" model). Then once you have scaled them as far as they want to go then start looking for companies to buy that you learned from these "one-off" projects. You can purchase these businesses  with creative financing, sometimes with no money out of your pocket. Then you have an asset that makes you whatever the business model has or could have. Then perfect it and buy more of the same type of businesses and then roll them up and if you don't want to it anymore sell it for 5-10x. This is how you can make real money in this game.
